Spatial Resolution and Mixed Pixels

Landscape-level analysis of satellite data often requires that pixels be classified. For example, quantifying changes in forest cover across time requires identifying which pixels represent forest. Images can be classified into only a few classes (e.g. forest or non-forest), or many classes representing complex landscapes. Mixed pixels, which record reflectance from more than one cover type, are problematic for classification.

In this exercise, you will simulate the spatial resolutions of three different satellite remote sensing platforms: PlanetScope, Sentinel2, and Landsat. By mapping out “pixels” on a heterogeneous landscape, you will demonstrate how changing the spatial resolution of remote sensing imagery affects our ability to classify it.

The main goals for the day are a) to experience firsthand the spatial resolution of some global satellite datasets, and b) to understand the limitations of representing complex land cover as a square pixel.

Part 1

Create your own artificial pixels on the ground and observe the landscape features that each one contains.

  1. Break into six groups.
  2. With your group members, locate your study site, which will be marked with a cone.
  3. Map out a 3-meter PlanetScope pixel around the cone, using a compass and the transect tape provided. Orient your imaginary grid towards true north. Mark the corners of the pixel with flags. (HINT: the magnetic declination at Loon Lake is +16°). You will have to adjust your compass accordingly. If you are using a compass app on your phone, make sure that true north is enabled.)
  4. Repeat step 3 for a 10-meter Sentinel 2 pixel and a 30-meter Landsat pixel.
  5. Decide if the pixel is mixed or homogenous.
  6. Note the features visible on the landscape.
  7. Consult your group and come up with a landcover class to assign to each pixel. This step is somewhat subjective; you can disagree with your group members!



Part 1 Discussion Questions

Add your answers to the table

  1. Is there one feature which is “dominant” on the landscape?
  1. Imagine each pixel in the year 2000. Look for clues about the site’s history. Do you think that you would have assigned it to a different landcover class 20 years ago?
  2. Is the value of a pixel determined equally by reflectance from the center and reflectance from the corners? In other words, does the sensor “see” the entire area represented by a pixel?


Part 2

Compare your observations to real satellite imagery of the study area and consider the spectral values of the real pixel corresponding to each site.

  1. Locate each site on the images of the study area and identify the pixel in the imagery corresponding to the site.
  2. Describe the pixel in the datasheet. What is its color? Does it have high or low reflectance? (If you’re color blind, don’t worry about wavelength. Just consider how much light is being reflected.)
  3. Look at the NDVI images and estimate the value for the pixel at each site. (https://gisgeography.com/ndvi-normalized-difference-vegetation-index/)


Now that you have practiced manually assigning values to a plot location, and comparing it to satellite imagery, let’s explore some other approaches for classifying landscapes.

Based on the information the NDVI gives us about vegetation vigour, we may make some inferences about landscape classes, and how they are distributed across our study area.

A simple way of doing this is via the use of a classification scheme. You will learn more about these in your courses throughout the MGEM program, but for our purposes here, we will be performing an unsupervised classification. Unsupervised classifications essentially group reflectance values together in a given number of classes, to which we can then assign some descriptor.

In this coding example, we split the NDVI values into 4 classes, to which we can then assign descriptive class names.

#first we want to specify the number of classes we are trying to detect. 
#In this case, let's go with 4
kMeansresult <- kmeans(Planet_NDVI[], centers = 4)

#Now we will take a "dummy" raster from our NDVI layer
result <- raster(Planet_NDVI)

#We can now take the classified raster values, and place them into our dummy raster
result <- setValues(result, kMeansresult$cluster)

#Let's take a look at our result!
plot(result)

The code above provides us with the NDVI values, split into 4 groups based on spectral similarity. Now we can move on to the next step, and add some descriptive labels to our classes.

#first we will have to switch from numeric to factor
raster <- as.factor(result)

#let's add a new column where we can store the classified land cover names
tar<-levels(raster)[[1]]

#Assign some names representative of the land cover
tar[["Landcover"]]<-c("Other Land cover", "This Land cover", "That Land cover", "Some Land cover")

#Now set the levels of your raster based on the land cover name column  you created
levels(raster)<-tar

#Plot and take a look at your handy work!
rasterVis::levelplot(raster, col.regions=c("Darkgreen", "Green", "Yellow", "Orange"))

Open an RStudio script on you laptop. Perform an unsupervised classification for the Landsat, Sentinel and Planet NDVI layers, assign class names, and compare the outputs.

Make sure that the colors and names you assign are representative of the landscape features you observed during your field visit.

Once you have completed the task above, you can use the code snippet below to derive the pixel values at each of your plot points. Do this for each of the satellite NDVI scenes.



#first, you will want to make sure the projection of the points is in the same projection as the rasters we're using. 
plot_locations <- spTransform(Plots, "+proj=utm +zone=10 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs")

#Now we can convert our points to a dataframe, and select the columns we will need. 
#In this case, we will only need the name of each plot location, along with the columns containing the coordinates. 
plot_locations <- as.data.frame(plot_locations)
plot_locations <- plot_locations %>%
  select("Name", "coords.x1", "coords.x2")

#We can now use the extract function to derive the raster values at each of our plot locations
pixel_values <- extract(raster, plot_locations[c(2,3)])

#combine the pixel values with the plots information
pointinfo <- cbind(plot_locations, pixel_values)

#We will want to add our labels to this as well, so we can refer back to the levels we set in the previous task. In order for us to merge them with the extracted values, we must make sure it has the same name (in this case, 'pixel_values')
names <- as.data.frame(levels(raster))
colnames(names)[1] <- "pixel_values"

#Now we have our plot 'pointinfo', as well as a dataframe containing the raster value / land cover class 'key'. Merge the two. 
pointinfo <- merge(pointinfo, names, by = "pixel_values")

#Finally, we can now select the columns we want to view:
pointinfo <- pointinfo %>%
  select("Name", "Landcover", "pixel_values")

#Visualize
knitr::kable(pointinfo, format = "html")
